WEBVTT

00:00:00.930 --> 00:00:04.155
Friends, welcome to Word on Fire Catholic Ministries.

00:00:04.696 --> 00:00:18.376
Word on Fire is an apostolate dedicated to the mission of evangelization, using media both old and new to share the faith on every continent and to facilitate an encounter with Christ and His Church.

00:00:19.117 --> 00:00:26.688
The efforts of Word on Fire engage the culture and bring the transformative power of God's Word where it is most needed.

00:00:26.708 --> 00:00:27.890
Today,

00:00:27.970 --> 00:00:35.998
We invite you to join Bishop Robert Barron as he preaches the Gospel and shares the warmth and light of Christ with each one of us.

00:00:41.143 --> 00:00:41.723
Let me speak with you.

00:00:41.763 --> 00:00:47.589
For as many years ago when I was a student at Mundelein Seminary, we had a great professor named Dr. Richard Issel.

00:00:47.909 --> 00:00:56.658
He was a psychologist and he taught these courses in counseling and one was called a member of the Psychology of Successful Parish Priesthood.

00:00:56.770 --> 00:00:58.152
Well, I took all of his courses.

00:00:58.172 --> 00:00:59.053
He was a great teacher.

00:00:59.113 --> 00:01:02.256
And one principle I remember from Issel is this.

00:01:02.436 --> 00:01:11.587
He said, if you want to be happy, stop worrying about being happy and get on with becoming fulfilled.

00:01:12.728 --> 00:01:21.298
Happiness, and Aristotle knew this too a long time before Dr. Issel, happiness is a kind of byproduct of fulfillment.

00:01:21.730 --> 00:01:25.375
The worst thing you can do is to turn inward and fuss about, why am I not happy?

00:01:25.395 --> 00:01:26.277
How do I become happy?

00:01:26.577 --> 00:01:27.719
Forget about being happy.

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:32.946
Become fulfilled and the happiness will take care of itself.

00:01:33.948 --> 00:01:43.221
Something similar I found in Jordan Peterson's Reflections where he says, self-consciousness is equivalent to misery.

00:01:43.782 --> 00:01:49.490
And what he means I think is this turning inward, the self-preoccupation

00:01:49.986 --> 00:01:51.568
is equivalent with misery.

00:01:52.529 --> 00:01:57.374
So you want to be psychologically healthy, well, forget about yourself.

00:01:57.975 --> 00:02:03.380
Stop fussing about yourself and get about the business of fulfillment.

00:02:04.301 --> 00:02:14.192
It's a very helpful principle I find, and I bet now those listening to me, when you find yourself most unhappy, it's like you're fussing about yourself.

00:02:14.212 --> 00:02:15.573
You're turned inward.

00:02:16.134 --> 00:02:19.858
You're worrying about what might have been and the mistakes you made,

00:02:20.226 --> 00:02:21.087
Forget about that.

00:02:21.127 --> 00:02:22.669
Forget about being happy.

00:02:22.709 --> 00:02:24.511
Get on with being fulfilled.

00:02:24.551 --> 00:02:30.918
In other words, there's a kind of extroverted quality that's associated with happiness.

00:02:31.438 --> 00:02:34.642
Well, I always think of this when I come across our reading for today.

00:02:34.682 --> 00:02:37.345
We're, you know, reading from the Great Sermon on the Mount.

00:02:37.745 --> 00:02:40.849
Jesus, you know, paradigmatic teaching.

00:02:42.310 --> 00:02:46.575
Jesus says to his disciples, you are the salt of the earth.

00:02:47.416 --> 00:02:49.458
You are the light of the world.

00:02:49.730 --> 00:02:51.912
you are a city set on a hill."

00:02:52.993 --> 00:02:56.998
So you say, okay, the sermon that Jesus gives is sort of the key to happiness.

00:02:57.058 --> 00:02:59.080
It begins with the beatitudes, right?

00:02:59.180 --> 00:03:00.441
Beatitude means happiness.

00:03:00.481 --> 00:03:02.664
So if I want to be happy, I better follow this.

00:03:03.024 --> 00:03:06.488
Well, look what he tells his followers to be.

00:03:08.510 --> 00:03:11.433
Something for the sake of the other.

00:03:12.254 --> 00:03:13.035
So look at the first one.

00:03:14.116 --> 00:03:16.018
You are the salt of the earth.

00:03:16.578 --> 00:03:24.867
Well, in Jesus' time in the ancient world, long before refrigeration, if you wanted to preserve meat, well, you would salt it.

00:03:25.688 --> 00:03:28.491
You wanted to enhance its flavor, and that's true today, of course, too.

00:03:28.531 --> 00:03:29.833
You put salt on it.

00:03:30.474 --> 00:03:33.697
What's one thing you never would do if you have guests over to your house?

00:03:34.038 --> 00:03:36.640
Well, I'm serving dinner, and here's a plate of salt for you.

00:03:37.942 --> 00:03:40.485
Salt is not salt for its own sake.

00:03:40.825 --> 00:03:45.170
Salt exists for the sake of the other.

00:03:46.818 --> 00:03:48.740
What's the role of the Christian in the world?

00:03:49.361 --> 00:03:53.926
It's not to be fussily preoccupied with his or her own happiness.

00:03:54.046 --> 00:03:57.389
Rather, it's to become something for the sake of the other.

00:03:59.071 --> 00:04:03.776
Salt makes things spicy and tasty and interesting.

00:04:04.937 --> 00:04:07.941
Salt preserves what's worth preserving.

00:04:09.022 --> 00:04:11.004
So what's the role of the Christian in the world?

00:04:11.044 --> 00:04:14.728
It's not, well, let me try to be as happy as I can be.

00:04:14.768 --> 00:04:16.690
Let me cultivate my own holiness.

00:04:16.770 --> 00:04:25.699
No, you will become happy and you'll become holy in the measure that you become someone for others.

00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:27.941
So what does it mean to be salt?

00:04:29.122 --> 00:04:32.465
To be the spicy element within the society.

00:04:32.605 --> 00:04:42.275
I mean that Christians would invade all the expressions of the secular culture, entertainment and sports and business and finance and everything.

00:04:43.216 --> 00:04:45.458
Christians invade that space in a

00:04:45.602 --> 00:04:53.756
spicy, salty way to bring something of the style and energy of Jesus into all these elements of life.

00:04:54.477 --> 00:05:00.046
See, a Christian should wake up every morning and say, not, well, how can I become happier today?

00:05:00.106 --> 00:05:04.213
But rather, how can I make the world more Christ-like?

00:05:04.834 --> 00:05:07.499
How can I be salt for the world?

00:05:08.140 --> 00:05:11.986
How can I spice things up and preserve what's worth preserving?

00:05:12.418 --> 00:05:18.325
I think everybody, your whole approach to spiritual life will shift if you think along those lines.

00:05:19.307 --> 00:05:20.188
And look at the second one.

00:05:20.348 --> 00:05:23.272
He says, you are the light of the world.

00:05:24.413 --> 00:05:26.175
Well, you never see light.

00:05:27.317 --> 00:05:29.520
Light in itself is not visible.

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:33.164
Rather, light is that by which we see other things.

00:05:34.005 --> 00:05:40.914
You walk into a dark room and you're disoriented until someone turns on the light and then, ah, now I can see what's in the room.

00:05:41.730 --> 00:06:02.492
I always think here of those, the church in Rome has a wonderful Caravaggio paintings and they're in the dark and you have to put little coins in a machine to light up the picture and then boom, the light comes on and there's the Caravaggio and all its splendor and you can see it for a few minutes and the lights go out and you got to put more money in.

00:06:04.455 --> 00:06:08.018
You, my followers as Jesus, you're the light of the world.

00:06:09.400 --> 00:06:11.282
You are that by which

00:06:11.586 --> 00:06:18.235
things become more visible and beautiful and appealing.

00:06:18.996 --> 00:06:23.102
People will see beautiful things because of you.

00:06:23.142 --> 00:06:27.628
Now see, what if you thought about your spiritual life in those terms?

00:06:27.848 --> 00:06:30.772
So my goal today is not to make myself happier.

00:06:30.792 --> 00:06:33.075
No, it's to make others happier.

00:06:34.197 --> 00:06:40.786
Being by my own style of being in the world a light that illumines others.

00:06:41.538 --> 00:06:46.486
Or think of, you know, I often use the example of halos around the heads of saints.

00:06:46.526 --> 00:06:48.028
How come they're depicted that way?

00:06:48.629 --> 00:06:50.572
Because the saint is a light for others.

00:06:52.815 --> 00:06:53.516
How should I live?

00:06:53.997 --> 00:06:55.339
Well, I look to a saint.

00:06:55.659 --> 00:06:59.706
A saint becomes like a luminosity on the road.

00:07:00.266 --> 00:07:02.189
Let's say I'm stumbling around in the dark.

00:07:02.209 --> 00:07:04.393
I don't know what direction my life should take.

00:07:04.813 --> 00:07:10.482
Well, then I see a saint and suddenly the light goes on and I can see where I'm going.

00:07:10.594 --> 00:07:18.062
I think of the role that Thomas Aquinas played in my own life when I was a 14-year-old kid and Thomas was like a light going on.

00:07:19.004 --> 00:07:32.679
Or think of someone who's, you know, they lost their way and they come across the story of a Maximilian Colbert or a Mother Teresa or the Little Flower and suddenly the luminosity of that personality lights up their path.

00:07:32.739 --> 00:07:34.261
They see where they're supposed to go.

00:07:34.281 --> 00:07:38.866
Huh, that's your job, Christian, in the world.

00:07:39.394 --> 00:07:47.463
What if you woke up every day and said, that's my job today, is by my own sanctity to become a light for others to see.

00:07:48.524 --> 00:07:51.507
And then this last image that we might not get as readily.

00:07:52.388 --> 00:07:54.631
You're a city set on the hill.

00:07:55.352 --> 00:07:58.375
We'll see, you know, we've got GPS and everything else and maps to navigate.

00:07:58.796 --> 00:08:05.503
But in the ancient world, they had to navigate in a more, I suppose, clumsy way.

00:08:06.084 --> 00:08:08.146
But one of the ways they navigated was

00:08:08.578 --> 00:08:11.461
they'd see cities on a hilltop.

00:08:11.481 --> 00:08:17.748
Oh, you've got to move in the direction of that city or you have to come to that city and then you've got to move further west or whatever it was.

00:08:18.308 --> 00:08:21.271
The city on the hill was a means of navigation.

00:08:21.291 --> 00:08:24.154
It was a landmark that everybody could see.

00:08:24.234 --> 00:08:33.664
Huh, that's your job, Christian, to be a city set on the hill so that everybody can get their bearings from you.

00:08:34.185 --> 00:08:35.186
Does that make sense?

00:08:35.458 --> 00:08:37.961
We're all wandering around trying to make our way to God.

00:08:38.362 --> 00:08:39.604
Well, how do I find the way?

00:08:39.624 --> 00:08:40.725
Well, look, there's that city.

00:08:40.765 --> 00:08:42.768
Oh, yeah, move in that direction.

00:08:43.609 --> 00:08:46.433
Well, that's exactly the role the saints play, isn't it?

00:08:47.795 --> 00:08:50.519
They give directionality to our lives.

00:08:51.039 --> 00:08:54.644
But what if you thought about your own spiritual life precisely in those terms?

00:08:55.325 --> 00:08:59.391
That your distinctiveness is not for you.

00:09:00.252 --> 00:09:04.658
It's for the sake of someone who's trying to find his or her way.

00:09:05.506 --> 00:09:09.210
your salt, your light, your city set on a hill.

00:09:09.911 --> 00:09:24.026
You know, this has occurred to me with all of this in mind, is look at Catholics in America, so my home country, how we kind of oscillate back and forth between extremes in a way.

00:09:24.747 --> 00:09:30.893
When Catholics arrived here, you know, let's say middle of the 19th century and on, we were arriving at a very Protestant culture.

00:09:30.913 --> 00:09:35.378
And so it was important for Catholics to maintain their distinctiveness

00:09:35.586 --> 00:09:41.735
And so parishes and Catholic schools and sort of a Catholic subculture developed.

00:09:42.216 --> 00:09:44.319
The stress was on distinctiveness.

00:09:44.439 --> 00:09:47.965
What makes us uniquely Catholic over and against the wider culture?

00:09:48.606 --> 00:09:49.507
Well, is that good?

00:09:49.788 --> 00:09:54.114
Yeah, because salt can lose its saltiness, right?

00:09:54.795 --> 00:09:56.197
And the light can go out.

00:09:56.658 --> 00:09:59.262
And the city built on the hill can be raised to the ground.

00:09:59.282 --> 00:10:01.906
And so, yes, you do have to be distinctive.

00:10:04.482 --> 00:10:07.967
But the purpose is not to rest in your own distinctiveness.

00:10:08.828 --> 00:10:17.461
The purpose is now to use your distinctiveness as a guide and a light and a spice for others, right?

00:10:17.481 --> 00:10:18.282
So think of this now.

00:10:18.322 --> 00:10:22.208
When Catholics first arrived here, they were kind of stressing distinctiveness.

00:10:22.669 --> 00:10:27.115
Now the years I was coming of age, after Vatican II, we went to the other extreme.

00:10:27.536 --> 00:10:34.386
The church was kind of so open to the world that it lost a sense of what makes it unique.

00:10:35.650 --> 00:10:41.621
The biblical principle is always this sort of tensive, healthily tensive principle.

00:10:42.302 --> 00:10:53.241
We are distinct, salty, luminous, elevated for the sake of the other, not for our own sake.

00:10:54.684 --> 00:11:00.274
What's distinctive to us uniquely Catholic is for the sake of the wider world.

00:11:00.386 --> 00:11:05.373
I'm not meant to kind of crouch behind walls and cultivate my private Catholicism.

00:11:05.553 --> 00:11:05.853
No, no.

00:11:07.175 --> 00:11:10.680
Indeed, katholos, Catholic, means according to the whole.

00:11:11.461 --> 00:11:13.283
The church exists for the world.

00:11:14.004 --> 00:11:16.147
We're distinctive for the sake of the world.

00:11:16.167 --> 00:11:20.433
All of that is implicit in these great images that Jesus uses.

00:11:20.913 --> 00:11:26.701
Now, let me just close by drawing some attention to reading number one, which is from the prophet Isaiah.

00:11:27.943 --> 00:11:30.386
So if you say, okay, what is it?

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:33.073
What is this distinctive quality?

00:11:33.174 --> 00:11:37.419
What makes us salty and spicy and luminous and so on?

00:11:38.120 --> 00:11:48.013
Well, listen to what Isaiah says in our first reading.

00:11:48.074 --> 00:11:57.366
Then your light will break forth like the dawn, and your wound shall quickly be healed.

00:11:57.646 --> 00:12:00.370
It's really interesting now, in light of what we've been talking about.

00:12:00.994 --> 00:12:01.875
What's the light?

00:12:02.276 --> 00:12:02.937
What's the light?

00:12:03.597 --> 00:12:05.460
These actions.

00:12:06.501 --> 00:12:12.369
Now, building upon this, the church develops the corporal works of mercy, which I've talked about a lot.

00:12:12.930 --> 00:12:19.058
Feed the hungry, give drink to the thirsty, clothe the naked, shelter the homeless, visit the imprisoned, right?

00:12:19.078 --> 00:12:22.683
Visit the sick, bury the dead, concrete things.

00:12:23.524 --> 00:12:26.288
And when you perform these acts of love, what happens?

00:12:27.589 --> 00:12:30.994
Your light will break forth like the dawn

00:12:32.258 --> 00:12:33.380
you'll be life for others.

00:12:33.460 --> 00:12:37.225
And then listen though, and your wound shall quickly be healed.

00:12:37.646 --> 00:12:38.527
What's the wound?

00:12:39.669 --> 00:12:40.510
I'm just not happy.

00:12:41.131 --> 00:12:42.533
I'm just not content.

00:12:43.174 --> 00:12:43.835
What's the matter?

00:12:44.977 --> 00:12:47.942
Don't turn inward and fuss about it.

00:12:48.002 --> 00:12:51.687
Remember Dr. Issel, you know, you want to be happy, forget about your happiness.

00:12:52.248 --> 00:12:54.331
You want to be holy, forget about your holiness.

00:12:55.433 --> 00:13:01.522
You want the wound healed, turn your life into a gift

00:13:01.922 --> 00:13:02.443
for others.

00:13:04.125 --> 00:13:10.872
Salt, light, city on the hill, and it looks like these concrete works of mercy.

00:13:11.713 --> 00:13:15.357
Here's just the last thing from Isaiah that I'll add to the works of mercy.

00:13:15.458 --> 00:13:26.290
Listen, if you remove from your midst oppression, false accusation, and malicious speech, then light shall rise for you.

00:13:27.042 --> 00:13:28.925
There it is again, where's the light gonna come from?

00:13:29.125 --> 00:13:33.452
Well, he adds these, which I think are very relevant to us today.

00:13:35.395 --> 00:13:38.580
Oppression, false accusation, malicious speech.

00:13:40.062 --> 00:13:43.106
Go online any time of the day or night.

00:13:43.868 --> 00:13:55.986
How often now in the social media context, we engage in just this kind of malicious speech, attacking people's characters, going after them.

00:13:56.834 --> 00:13:57.695
Remove that.

00:13:57.715 --> 00:13:58.536
You want to be happier?

00:13:58.576 --> 00:14:02.602
Remove that from your life and light will shine forth.

00:14:03.663 --> 00:14:06.827
Remember everybody, it's the extroverted move.

00:14:07.408 --> 00:14:09.390
It's the move out from yourself.

00:14:09.911 --> 00:14:12.334
The Christian exists not for herself.

00:14:12.975 --> 00:14:15.539
The Christian exists for the world.

00:14:16.119 --> 00:14:19.283
Light, salt, city set on the hill.

00:14:20.565 --> 00:14:21.266
And God bless you.

00:14:25.858 --> 00:14:29.472
Thank you for listening to this week's homily from Bishop Robert Barron.

00:14:29.894 --> 00:14:34.994
For more resources from Bishop Barron, please visit wordonfire.org.
